04356nam a22005055i 9780773564725DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735647257 a10.1515/97807735647252doi  a(DE-B1597)655953  a(OCoLC)732601127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQC774.L49bF39 1994eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a539.7/0921 aFawcett, Ruth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNuclear Pursuits :bThe Scientific Biography of Wilfrid Bennett Lewis /cRuth Fawcett. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAbbreviations -- tEarly Years -- tRadar Days -- tChalk River -- tNuclear and Other Pursuits -- t“The Gleam in the Eye of the Atomic Scientist”: Towards a Power Reactor -- tCanada’s Nuclear Statesman -- tIng -- tThe Power Program Revisited: 1959–73 -- tRetirement -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBorn in England in 1908, Lewis earned a doctorate at the Cavendish Laboratory in 1934 and continued his research on nuclear physics there until 1939. During the war he worked on the development of radar and in 1945 became chief superintendent of the Telecommunications Research Establishment at Malvern. A year later he agreed to head Canada's fledgling nuclear research facility at Chalk River, Ontario, where he made his professional home for the next twenty-seven years. Lewis's drive, intelligence, and remarkable organizational skills placed him at the forefront of Canada's nuclear program. Convinced that nuclear energy could be used economically for generating electricity, Lewis fostered a collaboration between Atomic Energy of Canada Limited (AECL) and Ontario Hydro that led to the development of the CANDU reactor. CANDU has proven to be an efficient reactor whose performance compares very favourably with all other power reactors around the world. Lewis's efforts in developing this design, and his effective support of a strong tradition of basic research, are his most important legacies. Under his guidance, scientists at AECL achieved excellence in a number of fields and the laboratories have maintained those standards to the present. Though not every project he promoted came to fruition, and he seemed never to recognize the political aspects of the nuclear energy program, Lewis's influence on the development of science, technology, and industry in Canada and abroad was unique and profound. His story sheds new light on Canada's postwar science history, debates concerning national science policy, and growing international scientific collaborations. Nuclear Pursuits will be of interest to a wide audience, including scientists, engineers, historians of science and industry, and students of postwar Canadian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356472540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564725/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles